abstract.label: Abstract
abstract.value:
Bruce D. Boling is a linguist, historian, and librarian whose research focused on the Irish language with specific emphasis on the English dialects spoken in Ulster. He also collaborated with historian Kerby A. Miller on several projects related to Irish immigration history, including 
                <emph render="italic">Irish Immigrants in the Land of Canaan: Letters and Memoirs from Colonial and Revolutionary America, 1675-1815</emph>. This collection documents Bruce Boling's research on the Irish language. Materials include maps, memoranda, correspondence, transcriptions and annotations of research material, journal articles on various aspects of linguistics, and original writing concerning aspects of English and Irish language dialects in Ulster. The collection provides resource materials not only on the history of Irish immigration and the changing nature of regional linguistic patterns, but also the way in which social scientists interrogate the intersection between linguistics and social history. The collection also documents developments in the field of Irish American historiography, including Boling's interdisciplinary focus and methodology.

Donated by Kerby A. Miller on the behalf of Bruce Boling in 2011.The accession number associated with this gift is 2011.041.

Using immigrants’ letters and other sources, Boling sought to reconstruct the Ulster region’s 18th- and 19th-century dialects. He also collaborated with historian Kerby Miller on several projects related to Irish immigration history, including 
                <emph render="italic">Irish Immigrants in the Land of Canaan: Letters and Memoirs from Colonial and Revolutionary America, 1675-1815</emph>.

This collection documents Bruce Boling's research on the Irish language. Materials include maps, memoranda, correspondence, transcriptions and annotations of research material, journal articles on various aspects of linguistics, and original writing concerning aspects of English and Irish language dialects in Ulster. The majority of the collection consists of materials produced in the process of researching and contributing to 
                <emph render="italic">Irish Immigrants in the Land of Canaan: Letters and Memoirs from Colonial and Revolutionary America, 1675-1815</emph>, including copies, transcriptions, and translations of 18th- and 19th-century Irish immigrants' letters to family members. The collection provides resource materials not only on the history of Irish immigration and the changing nature of regional linguistic patterns, but also the way in which social scientists interrogate the intersection between linguistics and social history. The collection also documents developments in the field of Irish American historiography, including Boling's interdisciplinary focus and methodology.

Series I. Research Files Subseries IA. General circa 1970-2000 Scope and Content Note

This subseries contains materials related to Boling's research interests and activities not directly related to the publication of Irish Immigrants in the Land of New Canaan. Materials include bibliographic notecards and research notes on linguistic matters not specific to the Irish language, in addition to annotated photocopies and transcriptions of various works of Irish-language poetry and literature.

Irish Immigrants in the Land of New Canaan 1959-2001 Scope and Content Note

This subseries contains materials related to the development and publication of Irish Immigrants in the Land of Canaan: Letters and Memoirs from Colonial and Revolutionary America, 1675-1815, an examination of Irish American migration written and edited by Kerby A. Miller, Bruce Boling, David N. Doyle, and Arnold Schrier. Materials include maps, census data for the time periods researched, notes from research visits to multiple archival repositories, correspondence with the other contributors, and reviews of the publication. The majority of the subseries consists of photocopies, transcriptions, and notes on the hundreds of letters written by Irish immigrants that Boling examined. Many folders contain not only copies of the letters, but extensive analysis of the grammatical, morphological, or phonological features present in these writings. Multiple folders show the process by which Boling and the other historians grouped these letters into distinct categories based on themes, time period, and the letter-writer's profession.

Original Writings and Presentations 1972-1995 Scope and Content Note

This series contains materials related to Boling's original writings or presentations delivered at various conferences. Materials include manuscripts, handouts, and transparencies. Topics include the evolution of the Irish language, the value of studying letters with regards to researching dialect, and the history of Irish immigration from a socio-linguistic perspective.

Secondary Source Materials 1905-2001 Scope and Content Note

This series contains bibliographies and scholarly journal articles on a variety of historical and linguistic subjects, ranging from general to specific. Many of the linguistic articles relate to grammatical, morphological, or phonological phenomena present in a particular language. The materials in this series represent scholarly journal articles related to the immediate areas of Boling's research interests - the historical evolution of the Irish language and English dialects in Ireland - in addition to historical linguistics topics present in a wide-range of languages, including French, German, Russian, Navajo, and Ukrainian.
